{{Unreferenced stub|auto=yes|date=December 2009}}
In [[cinematography]], '''night-for-night''' filming is the practice of actually filming night scenes at night.

In the early days of cinema, before the invention of the proper lighting systems, night scenes were filmed "[[day-for-night]]"--that is, they were filmed during the day, and the film was "corrected", either with a [[Polarization (waves)|polarized]] lens on the [[movie camera]], or via a variety of [[post-production]] techniques. Day-for-night shooting is still used in low-budget films.

The American television producer [[Quinn Martin]] was known for heavily utilizing night-for-night filming.<ref>Etter, Jonathan.  ''Quinn Martin, Producer''.  Jefferson:  McFarland, 2003.</ref><ref>http://www.museum.tv/eotv/martinquinn.htm</ref>
{{DEFAULTSORT:Night-For-Night}}
