[[File:Walter Van Brunt.jpg|thumb|1921 portrait of Van Brunt (as Walter Scanlan)]]
'''Walter Van Brunt''' (April 22, 1892 &ndash; April 11, 1971) was an [[United States|American]] tenor known initially for his recordings on [[Thomas Alva Edison]]'s [[Blue Amberol Records]] and later for his role in a scandal involving a [[stage name]] and case of [[adultery]].
==Biography== Van Brunt began his singing career at age 17 as an imitator of singer [[Billy Murray (singer)|Billy Murray]]. He was soon performing with [[Ada Jones]] and [[John Bieling]] as well as the [[American Quartet (ensemble)|American Quartet]]. He worked in [[vaudeville]] and on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]], including in the musical ''[[Eileen (musical)|Eileen]]''. Van Brunt had 40 hits on pop charts, including his 1914 duet with [[Elizabeth Spencer (soprano)|Elizabeth Spencer]].<ref>{{YouTube|wPGgaJMVQv8|Edmundsrex information on Walter Van Brunt}}, [[YouTube]]. Accessed 10 February 2010.</ref>
In 1917, Van Brunt began using the name '''Walter J. Scanlan''' (newspapers sometimes erroneously rendered the name as "Scanlon"), which was the name of a late 19th-century Irish tenor who had had an established career before dying but never made any recordings. It has been suggested, but not proved, that the [[Irish-American]] composer of ''[[Eileen (musical)|Eileen]]'', [[Victor Herbert]], had encouraged the use of this stage name when he cast Van Brunt as the leading man. It was not a secret that this was a stage name: ''[[The New York Times]]'' review of ''Eileen'' stated that Scanlan’s real name was Van Brunt.<ref>"''Eileen'' Brim Full of Rich Melodies", ''The New York Times'', March 20, 1917, p. 9</ref> Van Brunt later had a bigamous affair with a woman known as Ruth Scanlan, siring a child with her and prompting his wife Lillian to sue for divorce, which was granted in 1925 by an [[Irish-American]] judge who, in announcing his decision that Van Brunt should pay alimony, criticized Van Brunt's character.<ref>Allan Sutton, [http://www.mainspringpress.com/vanbrunt.html "The Walter Scanlan Scandal: The Rest of the Walter Van Brunt Story"] on Mainspring (accessed 10 February 2010). Van Brunt, as indicated by the [[tussenvoegsel]] ''Van'', was of Dutch not Irish extraction.</ref>
From 1929 to 1933, Murray used Van Brunt on various radio programs.<ref>[http://www.songwritershalloffame.org/artists/C4059 "Walter Van Brunt"] listing among the "Songwriters' Friends", [http://www.songwritershalloffame.org/ Songwriters Hall of Fame]. Accessed 10 February 2010.</ref> In 1929, Scanlon and Billy Murray provided the voices for the Fleischer short animation film ''[[Finding His Voice]]'', produced by [[Western Electric]].
